in all project we have some files that we want to
git don't track them, just ignore them!
like environment variables that we define in spring 2 to store our secret keys.
we dont want to log files and built in classes (like /out )
make our repository large.

we can add these files on ".gitignore" file
we can create ".gitignore" manually
or when we create a repository on git-hub it has option to create it
".gitignore should be in ** ROOT **  of the project"

Important Note: we should ignore these file before staging!
                it means before first time we use "git add ."
                if we move these file to stage, gitignore will not work!
                because git will track all the file on stage area!

                if we add these file to stage accidentally,
                we should remove them before committing, and prevent to remain in history
                (remove from index, but remained on disk)
                it's what happened on spring 2.

1. we create .gitignore on root spring 2 manually
   and put our ignored files there
   but I used git add . (so I put them on stage)

2. I used some commands to remove some files from stage
   git rm --cached -r .env                          cached: means remove them from index (not from disk)
                                                            cached means they cashed by stage
   git rm --cached -r .idea/                        r     : means recursively, remove sub folders

Note: we can find --cached        git rm -h
      by git help:


3. we have some templates for .gitignore based on language
   we can find these templates on "github.com/github/gitignore"
   I just ignore some:

   .idea/
   *.iml
   out/
   target/              //create by MAVEN after compile
   .DS_Store            //some file that OS added when use finder to explore folders
   *.log                //every logged file (* is pattern)
   .env                 //oue keys
